{"id": "duc04-testb-49:6#18", "contents": "When the world's finance ministers and central bankers gathered last year in Hong Kong, they congratulated each other for containing, at least for the moment, a nasty financial brush fire in Asia. Many predicted that the troubles in Thailand and Indonesia would look like a replay of Mexico in 1995 \u2013 a rough bump in the road for a world enjoying remarkable prosperity. However, twelve months later, the world economy has taken a turn for the worse. The worst downturn in Japan since World War II, economic meltdown in Russia, a depression in Indonesia, and deep fears over what happens next in Latin America have all come to pass. The IMF meeting this year is remarkable for the harsh criticisms directed at the monetary fund itself and the U.S. Treasury, which is viewed as the power behind the IMF."}
